                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Just on the topic of weight loss in general, I recently read that just over 1/4 Americans are obese. Obese means overweight to the point of health issues, where they notice you're more likely to have heart troubles etc. Obesity is deturmined using your <a href="http://www.consumer.gov/weightloss/bmi.htm" target="_blank" class="postlink">Body Mass Index</a>.  
<br />

<br />
I think it's fair to say if you're in the obese range it's time to consult your doctor, find out about what might be causing it and how you can work on it. If you're in the overweight range you may want to consider some lifestyle changes just as a preventative measure.  This gives you a pretty good idea of when you should be concerned about your weight. 
<br />

<br />
One of the things I firmly believe is that a big part of loving yourself means taking care of your body. Genetics, thyroid issues, and a variety of other factors beyond our control make our bodies different, but no matter what we get we need to do our best with it - not like we can just turn it in for a new one.  <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" /></span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />e^(i*Pi) + 1 = 0</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
