                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Generally, I agree with the statement that feeling good about yourself is never a cop out, as long as you're healthy.  If you don't feel healthy, something needs to change--maybe the amount of light exercise, maybe your diet--but if you're happy and can do a few flights of stairs without getting badly winded, you're probably better than most Americans.
<br />

<br />
Living in Japan, being paranoid about my weight is something I have to live with every day.  Compared to women here, I am morbidly obese.  It can really get to you to go clothes shopping and only be able to wear the XXL muumuus (in America, mind you, I'm probably about average...which isn't thin, of course).  But I eat fairly well and I walk about 30 minutes a day to and from work, so I feel pretty good about myself. 
<br />

<br />
Oh, and I heartily second the warnings about stomach stapling, on a slightly off-topic.  I had two friends of my mother's do it.  The first gained all her weight back eventually anyway (the staples gave way) and only lost weight when she changed her eating lifestyle (not Atkins but the same idea).  The second...well, she lapsed into a coma for a month and almost died.  But she did lose a lot of weight while in the coma.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><img src="http://home.att.ne.jp/apple/dmolden/screenshots/pixcol.gif" border="0" />
<br />
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=611032" target="_blank" class="postlink">Columbyne Celebfin</a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
