                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I agree with Craftah. Imho dieting only makes things worse. It's important to choose a way of life when it comes to eating. Unlearn bad habits and learn new ones.
<br />

<br />
After I was sick many years ago I went on a fairly strict Macrobiotic diet (for the sake of my health) and I noticed after the first 2 months (which were very difficult) that my entire approach to food had changed. This wasn't really what I had intended. Initially I couldn't stand the taste of brown rice... but over time I found that my tastes had changed. I found that my tongue (for lack of a better word) could no longer handle the taste of really strong processed foods like Cheetohs (by the way I had a serious Cheetoh weakness) or Cookies etc. I still enjoyed these things, I just couldn't eat very much of them because the flavours would overwhelm. Anyway, it's difficult to explain exactly, but, what I'm trying to say is that after I cleared my system (again for lack of a better phrase) I found that I no longer craved things that I used to crave or at least not with the same intensity. Veggies and unprocessed foods just tasted better to me. And the best part of all, was I found myself not looking in the refrigerator trying to find something to satisfy me. I think everyone knows what I mean. The perfunctory look in the frig trying to find that one thing that will satisfy the ominous food want... That just completely stopped for me. I started to feel satisfied with the flavours and the foods I was eating. Its was really an unexpected experience for me. And even though I'm not practicing a strict Macrobiotic diet today, I still have carried over a lot of those food values. It changed me permanently and I rarely overeat now unless I purposefully intend to. <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
Anyway, I wouldnt necessarily recommend a Macrobiotic diet (although I really loved it). But something like Atkins or anything where youre training your body to respond differently to food only leads to a good thing. 
<br />

<br />
It wasnt easy for me especially leaving large quantities of sugar behind but wow, what a difference it makes in your life or made in mine.
<br />

<br />
And, of course this is when I found out my thyroid had gone buggy. So I would recommend that if anyone is concerned about hypo- or hyper-thyroidism they take the time to see an Endocrinologist. I dont mean this as a quick fix to finding way to lose weight, but, I will say at that certain points prior to my beginning thyroid medication I was eating 1200  1500 calories a day and exercising (jogging on a treadmill and Stairmaster type stuff) 5 times a weak and I never lost a single pound until I got my thyroid treated. But, that was my experience and I had done a Chemotherapy regiment that had damaged my thyroid. At the time, after the treatment I had gone from 130pounds to 180 or so it was a hard time. 
<br />

<br />
I did want to say to Juwel, apparently there are many, many women who after pregnancy have developed a thyroid problems and arent aware of the change theyve experienced. So again, you might want to talk to an Endocrinologist if you have the opportunity. Ironically, Ill be visiting my Endocrinologist on Monday so maybe Ill ask him if he has any information I can pass on to people who are concerned</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
